  "answer": "**I'm unable to locate this exact couplet in the Falsafa corpus.**\n\nThe *Diwan-e-Ghalib* (mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c) is present as a complete collection of 239 ghazals.[^1] Searches across its English translations for phrases like \"Rah-rau ki manzil,\" \"wayfarer,\" \"destination,\" \"caravan,\" \"qafila,\" or \"no destination nor caravan\" yielded no matches. Several ghazals evoke similar themes of wandering, deserts (*sahra*), journeys (*dasht-nawardi*), or receding destinations (*doori-e-manzil*), such as:\n\n- Ghazal 67: \"With every step, the goal recedes in vain from me...\"[^2]\n- Ghazal 223: \"To halt my desert-wandering, all schemes are vain...\"[^3]\n- Ghazal 228: \"My wandering feet are pinned, though I must go...\"[^4]\n\nHowever, none begin with the specified line or contain the described wording in translation. The original Urdu or transliteration variants exist but cannot be searched via available tools (which target English only). If this is from a specific edition outside this corpus, it's not covered here.\n\n[^1]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, full metadata: [link](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/metadata/).\n\n[^2]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, Chapter 67, [translation](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/67-har-qadam-doori-e-manzil-hai-numayan-mujh-se/translation/).\n\n[^3]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, Chapter 223, [translation](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/223-maane-e-dasht-nawardi-koi-tadbeer-nahin/translation/).\n\n[^4]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, Chapter 228, [translation](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/228-pa-ba-daaman-ho-raha-hoon-baske-main-sahra-navard/translation/).",
